      "title": "Orthogonal Trajectories of a given Curve",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Orthogonal Trajectory of a Given Curve&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Any curve, which cuts every member of a given family of curvs at right angle, is called an orthogonal trajectory of the family.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"410\" height=\"155\"></p><p>Procedure:</p><ol><li>Let $f\\left( x,y,c \\right)=0$ be the eqaution where c is an arbitrary parameter</li><li>Differentiate the given equation w.r.t. x and eliminate c</li><li>Substitute $-\\frac{dx}{dy}$ for $\\frac{dy}{dx}$ in the equation obtained in step (ii)</li><li>Solve the differential equation obtained from step (iii).</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the orthogonal trajectories of the curve $y=a{{x}^{2}}$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\text{y}=\\text{a}{{\\text{x}}^{2}}$ ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating equation (i), we get</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{dy}}{\\text{dx}}=2\\text{ax}$ ...(ii)</p><p>Eliminating a from equation (i) &amp; (ii), we get</p><p>$\\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{2y}{{{x}^{2}}}x$ ...(iii)</p><p>Putting $-\\frac{dx}{dy}$ in equation (iii) in place of $\\frac{dy}{dx}$, we get</p><p>$\\frac{-\\text{dx}}{\\text{dy}}=\\frac{2\\text{y}}{\\text{x}}$ $\\Rightarrow -xdx=2ydy$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow -\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{2}=\\frac{2{{y}^{2}}}{2}$ $\\Rightarrow 2{{y}^{2}}+{{x}^{2}}=0$</p><p>This is the family of required orthogonal trajectories.</p><p><strong>Note : </strong>All the curves in this family of curves are orthogonal to the given family of curves.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the orthogonal trajectory of teh curve ${{a}^{n-1}}y={{x}^{n}}$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Given curve is ${{a}^{n-1}}y={{x}^{n}}$ ...(i)</p><p>Differentiating equation (i) w.r.t. x, we get ${{a}^{n-1}}\\frac{dy}{dx}=n{{x}^{n-1}}$ ...(ii)</p><p>Eliminating a from equation (i) &amp; (ii) we get</p><p>$\\frac{{{x}^{n}}}{y}\\frac{dy}{dx}=n{{x}^{n-1}}$ ...(iii)</p><p>Putting $-\\frac{dx}{dy}$ in equation (iii) in place of $\\frac{dy}{dx}$, we get</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; -\\frac{{{x}^{n}}}{y}\\cdot \\frac{dx}{dy}=n{{x}^{n-1}}\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\Rightarrow \\frac{-xdx}{ydy}=n\\,\\,\\,\\,\\Rightarrow -xdx=nydy \\\\ &amp; \\Rightarrow -\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{2}+c=\\frac{n{{y}^{2}}}{2}\\Rightarrow n{{y}^{2}}+{{x}^{2}}=\\text{ constant }. \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Q) Find the orthogonal trajectories of the circles ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}-ay=0$ where $a$ is a parameter.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Here, ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}-ay=0$ : differentiating w.r.t. $x$,</p><p>$\\begin{align} &amp; 2x+2y\\frac{dy}{dx}-a\\frac{dy}{dx}=0 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore 2x+2y\\frac{dy}{dx}-\\frac{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}{y}\\frac{dy}{dx}=0\\quad \\left( \\because {{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}-ay=0\\Rightarrow a=\\frac{{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}}{y} \\right)\\text{ } \\\\ &amp; \\text{or }2x+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}}{y}\\frac{dy}{dx}=0. \\\\ \\end{align}$</p><p>This is the differential equation of the circle. The equation of orthogonal trajectories is</p><p>$2x+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}}{y}\\cdot \\left( -\\frac{dx}{dy} \\right)=0,\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\,\\,\\,\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ putting }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{-dx}{dy}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ in }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ place }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{dy}{dx} \\right)$</p><p>or $2xydy+\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right)dx=0$.</p><p>It is a homogeneous equation.</p><p>Put $y=vx;$ then $\\frac{dy}{dx}=v+x\\frac{dy}{dx}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,\\,2x\\cdot vx\\cdot \\left( v+x\\frac{dv}{dx} \\right)+{{x}^{2}}-{{v}^{2}}{{x}^{2}}=0$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }2\\text{v}\\left( \\text{v}+\\text{x}\\frac{\\text{dv}}{\\text{dx}} \\right)+1-{{\\text{v}}^{2}}=0\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }1+{{\\text{v}}^{2}}+2\\text{vx}\\frac{\\text{dv}}{\\text{dx}}=0$</p><p>or $\\frac{dx}{x}+\\frac{2v}{1+{{v}^{2}}}dv=0;$ integrating, we get $\\text{log}\\,x+\\text{log}\\left( 1+{{v}^{2}} \\right)=\\text{log}c$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ x}\\left( 1+{{\\text{v}}^{2}} \\right)=\\text{c}$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }x\\left( 1+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{x}^{2}}} \\right)=c$, i.e., ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}=cx$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd4dc03b9dcaf1afea46"
    }
